Disease_description:
Diagnosis Task: I am a 34 year old male and have been having unilateral pain behind my right eye every night for weeks. This one wakes me up almost always at the same time, around 1:00 am. It feels like a knife behind the eye, so severe that the eye is watery and all red. When I get up and walking around in my appartment, it is better after about 1 hour. Eye and ENT doctors have not found anything. My dentist has also not been able to get any improvement with a root canal. I have also tried to take aspirin or diclofenac against the pain, but unfortunately neither brings anything. Apart from that, I am a smoker and have higher blood pressure more often. What are most likely diagnoses? Name up to five.

  True Disease: Cluster headache

  Model Output:Based on your symptoms, there are a few potential diagnoses that could be causing your unilateral pain behind your right eye. Here are five possible conditions that you may want to discuss with your healthcare provider:&#xA;&#xA;Cluster headaches: These headaches typically cause severe, excruciating pain around one eye that can last for weeks or months. They often occur at the same time each day or night, and can be triggered by smoking or changes in blood pressure.&#xA;Migraine headaches: Migraines can also cause intense pain behind one eye, as well as other symptoms such as nausea, sensitivity to light and sound, and visual disturbances.&#xA;Sinusitis: An infection or inflammation of the sinuses can cause pain behind the eyes, especially if it is affecting the sinuses located around the nose and eyes.&#xA;Glaucoma: This condition can cause pain and pressure behind the eyes, as well as vision changes and other symptoms. It is more common in people with high blood pressure.&#xA;Temporomandibular joint disorder (TMJ): Problems with the joint that connects the jawbone to the skull can cause pain in the face and head, including behind the eyes. Smoking and high blood pressure can also contribute to TMJ issues.&#xA;&#xA;It's important to note that there could be other potential causes for your symptoms as well, and a healthcare provider would be best equipped to make a diagnosis after conducting a thorough evaluation.&#xA;&#xA;

Diagnosis Task: My 10 year old daughter has had a cold and cough for a week. She was actually feeling better until she suddenly developed a high fever. In addition, she now complains of severe frontal headaches, which are particularly bad whenever she tilts her head forward. What are most likely diagnoses? Name up to five.

  True Disease: Acute sinusitis and rhinosinusitis

  Model Output:I am not a doctor, but I can try to help you think about some possibilities. If your daughter's symptoms have worsened suddenly, it's important to consult with a healthcare professional for an accurate diagnosis and appropriate treatment. That being said, here are five possible conditions that could be related to her symptoms:&#xA;&#xA;Sinusitis: Inflammation or infection of the sinuses can cause symptoms such as a high fever, headache (particularly in the frontal area), and a worsening cough. Headaches may be worse when tilting the head forward.&#xA;Meningitis: This is a serious infection of the membranes surrounding the brain and spinal cord. Symptoms may include a high fever, severe headache, and a stiff neck. Meningitis can be life-threatening and requires immediate medical attention.&#xA;Influenza: Commonly known as the flu, this viral infection can cause high fever, headache, body aches, and cough. Symptoms can sometimes worsen after initial improvement.&#xA;Pneumonia: An infection in the lungs may present with symptoms like high fever, cough, and headache. Pneumonia can sometimes develop as a complication of a cold or flu.&#xA;Secondary bacterial infection: Sometimes, a cold or viral infection can be complicated by a bacterial infection, leading to symptoms like high fever and worsening of the initial symptoms.&#xA;&#xA;Again, it's crucial to consult with a healthcare professional for a proper evaluation, diagnosis, and treatment plan.&#xA;&#xA;
